Philippine Stocks: Manila Electric, Philippine National Bank

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-10-18T05:11:53Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-18/bank-of-philippine-islands-splash-philippine-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the close in  Manila .  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index decreased 1.4 percent
to 4,157.26, snapping an eight-day rally. The measure posted its
sharpest loss since Oct. 3.  Manila Electric Co. (MER)  , the nation’s biggest power
retailer, declined 2.8 percent to 240 pesos, its first loss in
three days, after CitisecOnline.com Inc. analyst George Ching
cut 2011 and 2012 profit forecasts for the power distributor.  Metro Pacific Investments Corp. (MPI)   retreated 1.6
percent to 3.07 pesos. Metro Pacific Tollways Corp., operator of
the nation’s longest tollroad and a unit of the company, said it
will likely miss its 7 billion-peso ($162 million) revenue
target this year because of higher fuel costs, toll fees and bad
weather.  Philippine National Bank (PNB)   sank 3.5 percent to 55
pesos, the first drop in nine days, after the stock was cut to
“hold” from “buy” by Katherine Tan, an analyst at ATR KimEng
Securities Inc. Philippine National posted its sharpest decrease
since Sept. 26.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
